<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1905-06-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1905-06-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="856" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d856">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to Ambassador <persName type="to">Meyer</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1905-06-30"><hi rend="italic">June 30,
                                1905</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 45.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I inclose copy of a note from the Japanese
                            minister at this capital, asking the use of your good offices for the
                            release of three Japanese merchants captured in the northern part of
                            Korea about May, 1904.<note n="c" xml:id="d856fnc">Printed under Japan,
                                    <ref target="#pg_602">p. 602</ref>.</note> Their names are said
                            to be Nobe Ichitaro, Yagabe Chiuzaburo, and Gyo, the son of the
                            latter.</p>
                        <p>The Department desires you to comply with the minister’s request.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Herbert H. D.
                            Peirce.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>